The Standard gives con siderable ﬂ exibility to compilers when evaluating expressions. Most operators
can have their operands evaluated in any order. The main exceptions are:
• Logical AND && in w h ich the second operand is evaluated only if the ﬁ rst operand evaluates
to non-zero;
• Logical OR || in wh ich the second operand is evaluated only if the ﬁ rst operand evaluates to
zero;
• The conditional operator ?: in wh ich the ﬁ rst operand is always evaluated and then either the
second or third operand is evaluated;
• The , operat or in which the ﬁ rst operand is evaluated and then the second operand is
evaluated.
Note: The presence of parentheses may alter the order in which operators are applied. However, this
does not a ﬀ ect the order of evaluation of the lowest-level operands, which may be evaluated in any
order.
Many of the common instances of the unpredictable behaviour associated with expression evaluation
can be avoided by following the advice given by Rule 13.3 and Rule 13.4.
